    <section>
      <h2>Why Augusta?</h2>
      <p>Augusta is Maine's state capital and the political heart of the state. About 19,000 people live here year-round, but the greater Augusta area reaches approximately 60,000 residents who commute in for government services, healthcare appointments, and regional shopping. The city's economy is driven primarily by state government, MaineGeneral Medical Center, and the University of Maine at Augusta campus. This creates a stable economic base less exposed to tourism swings or seasonal fluctuations that affect coastal markets.</p>
      <p>The stable customer base makes Augusta attractive for a different reason than Portland or Bangor. While other markets chase tourist dollars or fight for market share among residents, Augusta draws a consistent regional population. State workers, healthcare employees, and university students form predictable customer segments with regular schedules and reliable incomes.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="Access to the Policy Makers" type="info">
      Augusta hosts Maine's legislature and executive agencies. Dispensary owners here interact regularly with the people who write cannabis rules. A visible, well-run operation in Augusta can shape industry policy. That access is not available in any other Maine market. Several current OCP staff members are known to shop at local dispensaries—being a known, trusted operator here carries weight that carries over to licensing discussions and compliance reviews.
    </Callout>

