    <section>
      <h2>The Capital Advantage</h2>
      <p>Augusta's connection to state government creates unique opportunities that no other Maine market offers. Legislators, agency staff, policy advocates, and lobbyists are constant presences on Water Street and around the State House complex. These decision-makers see the same businesses every day during the legislative session.</p>
      <p>A dispensary near the State House—particularly along Water Street between the Capitol building and Memorial Square—builds name recognition among the people who determine the industry's future. This is not speculation; Maine's cannabis regulations are actively debated, and operators who are known quantities to policymakers have historically had more influence over rulemaking than operators in other markets.</p>
      <p>Beyond politics, Augusta draws regional residents for healthcare, shopping, and government services. MaineGeneral Medical Center alone employs over 2,000 people and serves patients from a wide swath of central Maine. Hospital workers, patients, and visitors constitute a distinct customer segment that visits Augusta regularly for appointments and support services.</p>
      <p>The UMaine Augusta campus adds a younger demographic to the mix. Students and faculty from the university visit downtown regularly for classes, events, and social activities. This segment tends to be price-conscious but open to trying new products and brands. They represent the long-term customer base that every dispensary needs to cultivate.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Augusta's Current Cannabis Landscape</h2>
      <p>Three to four licensed dispensaries currently operate in the Augusta area. This is moderate competition by Maine standards—more than Winthrop or Winlsow, fewer than Portland or Bangor. The existing stores cluster around Western Avenue and the downtown area, leaving gaps in the Civic Center Drive corridor and along the northern approach to the city.</p>
      <p>The existing stores have established relationships with regular customers, but the market is not saturated. Augusta's stable regional draw means new customers enter the market regularly. State workers transferred from other areas, newly registered medical patients, and UMaine Augusta students arriving each fall all represent potential new customers who have no existing loyalty to established stores.</p>
      <p>Augusta does not have the same tourism-driven weekend spikes that Portland experiences, but it also does not have the same deep troughs. Weekday traffic from government workers and healthcare employees provides a steadier baseline. This makes staffing and inventory planning more predictable than in tourist-dependent markets.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Capital Advantage</h2>
      <p>Augusta's connection to state government creates unique opportunities. Legislators, agency staff, and policy advocates are constant presences. A dispensary near the State House or on Water Street can build relationships with the people who determine the industry's future.</p>
      <p>Beyond politics, Augusta draws regional residents for healthcare, shopping, and government services. This regional draw creates a steady flow of new customers beyond the local population.</p>
      <p>UMaine Augusta's campus adds a younger demographic. Students and faculty from the university visit downtown regularly. They are another distinct customer segment in an otherwise government-dominated market.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Local Rules and Licensing</h2>
      <p>Augusta operates under Maine's adult-use cannabis framework, which means you need both a state OCP Adult-Use Retail License and local approval from the Augusta City Council or Planning Board. The local approval process typically requires a public hearing and a site plan review.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>State License:</strong> OCP Adult-Use Retail License from Maine's Office of Cannabis Policy</li>
        <li><strong>Local Approval:</strong> Site plan review and conditional use approval from the Augusta Planning Board</li>
        <li><strong>Local Annual Fee:</strong> $2,000-3,000 paid to the City of Augusta</li>
        <li><strong>School Buffer:</strong> 500-foot minimum from any school, measured property line to property line</li>
        <li><strong>Zoning:</strong> Commercial and Village Center zones only—residential zones are explicitly prohibited</li>
        <li><strong>Security:</strong> Must meet Maine OCP security requirements including surveillance systems and locked storage</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The Augusta Planning Department holds regular meetings on the second and fourth Thursdays of each month. Your application must be submitted at least 30 days before a meeting to be considered in that cycle. Budget accordingly when planning your launch timeline.</p>
    </section>

