    <section>
      <h2>Real Estate Considerations</h2>
      <p>Augusta's commercial landscape centers on a few key corridors. Water Street runs from the State House down toward the Kennebec River. It is the most visible street in the city and attracts government workers, downtown visitors, and local residents. Western Avenue is the retail strip that parallels I-95. It draws regional shoppers and travelers passing through. Civic Center Drive hosts the shopping center and medical facilities.</p>
      <p>Square footage for a dispensary typically runs 1,200-1,800 square feet. Commercial rent in Augusta ranges from $10-$18 per square foot annually. Water Street commands the highest rents due to State House proximity. Western Avenue and Civic Center Drive offer more affordable options with good highway visibility.</p>
      <p>The 500-foot school buffer affects certain parcels near Cony High School and the middle schools. Your zoning attorney should verify your chosen location against school district maps before committing.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>What Makes Augusta Different</h2>
      <p>Augusta's customer base is different from Portland or Lewiston. The government presence creates a daytime population that disappears in the evening. State offices close at 5pm. The State House activity peaks during the legislative session (January to June). These patterns affect your staffing and sales projections.</p>
      <p>The healthcare sector is equally important. MaineGeneral Medical Center employs thousands of people in the Augusta area. Healthcare workers have stable incomes and regular schedules. They are reliable customers who visit consistently. Consider how your product selection serves this demographic.</p>
      <p>UMaine Augusta adds a younger element to the market. Students tend to be price-conscious but open to trying new products. Faculty and staff are more discretionary in their purchasing. Both segments are worth cultivating.</p>
    </section>

